    {
      "code": "ast-x-leon",
      "role": "adstrate",
      "weight": 0.02,
      "notes": "Asturleonese/Leonese adstrate: the Kingdom of Asturias and León was the dominant political power of Christian Iberia during the formative period of Galaico-Portuguese (8th–12th c.). The Leonese chancery language influenced administrative writing conventions, shared the 4-way sibilant system, and contributed some lexical and phonological features across the border. The split between the Galaico-Portuguese and Asturleonese traditions became clear only after the County of Portugal's independence (~1139)."
    }
  ],
  "notes": "Galaico-Portuguese (~9th–14th c. CE). The shared ancestor of modern Galician and Portuguese. Attested in troubadour lyric poetry (Cantigas de Santa Maria, cantigas de amigo, cantigas de amor — >1,600 texts), early legal documents (Notícia de Torto ~1214, Testamento de D. Afonso II ~1214). KEY FEATURES: (1) Medieval 4-way sibilant contrast: /ts/ ⟨ç⟩ vs /d͡z/ ⟨z⟩ vs /s/ ⟨ss⟩ vs /z/ ⟨-s-⟩. (2) /ʎ/ ⟨lh⟩, /ɲ/ ⟨nh⟩ digraph convention from Occitan. (3) /b/ ≠ /v/ preserved. (4) F- preserved (filho, not hijo). (5) /ou/ still a true diphthong. (6) Nasal vowels developing but not fully phonemicised. The split into Galician and Portuguese is conventionally dated to ~mid-14th c. when the Portuguese court settled in Lisbon and Galician fell under Castilian influence. Source: Maia (1986), Castro (2006), Teyssier (1982).",
